title: SOP_ Menu Tags Guidelines (1).docx — 1\.0 Objective
text: This document outlines the process of adding tags across different markets, details the relevant policies, and defines the responsibilities of various teams involved\. Tags play a vital role in improving the brand search experience on our Careem application\. We concentrate on three specific types of tags: Cuisine Tag, Tag Tags and Subpage Tags\. Adhering to established guidelines is essential for effective branding and improving the user experience\.

title: SOP_ Menu Tags Guidelines (1).docx — 4\.1 Tags process for the onboarding tickets
text: Including cuisine and tags is essential in the onboarding process for new brands\. When the Sales team creates an onboarding ticket, they should attach the MIF file \([see the Partner Onboarding Playbook](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1I7vKJ_r39B9N3ZacCcDuclfmOP8wYuN_/edit)\), which contains the relevant cuisine and tags\. They should also review the tags tree, identify up to two key values from the "__subtags__" column in [the cuisine tree](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/12sl32Ujfad6bd2TL73MwWOhPP9j10Aazs-diRl89Y6E/edit?gid=1902019320#gid=1902019320) that best represent the restaurant’s offerings, and clearly enter these values in the Jira ticket description\.

title: SOP_ Menu Tags Guidelines (1).docx — 2\.0 Scope
text: This document outlines the tagging policies for onboarding new restaurants as well as existing outlets \(clean\-up exercise\), across all food markets\.

title: SOP_ Menu Tags Guidelines (1).docx — 3\.0 Types of Tags
text:
Below are the tag types that enhance brand search functionality in food delivery apps\. Tags highlight key offerings, categorize specialties, improve search efficiency, and ensure consistent visibility across app features\.
There are three types of tags:
1. __Cuisine Tags: __These highlight a restaurant's main value proposition and are visible on the restaurant card in the app, with a maximum of three tags displayed\. These tags are integrated into selection tiles, carousels, and search functions for uniformity\.
2. __Tag Tags: __These hidden tags improve search and sorting by helping to organize and retrieve the restaurant during searches\. It specifically pertains to key menu items offered by the restaurant\.
3. __Subpage Tags: __These hidden tags are designed for sorting and displaying restaurants within subpages or subtiles in the app\. Connected with the subpage tiles, Subpage Tags enable better organization of restaurants within specific sections under the app’s main page\.

text:
Cuisine tags are divided into G1 and G2 types\. The repository linked below guides mapping G1 tags, and G2 tags against the Cuisine tags\. The process of tagging is shared here [cuisine tags sheet](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1I7sN0uRWrOHeP3qOv2djrFWEILEMez7dE7ivfp23jj4/edit?gid=120990296#gid=120990296)\. __Cuisine \(1&2\): Geographical tags__
1. __Cuisine Tag 1 \(G1\): __Represents country\-specific cuisine and must be sourced from the MIF\. If multiple tags are provided, and they come from the same tree \(e\.g\., Emirati, Saudi, Egyptian\), then G2 needs to be picked by the Catalog team\. If the tags come from different trees, the Catalog team will select the G1 tag based on the partner’s menu and the outlet name\. 2. __Cuisine Tag 2 \(G2\)__: Represents the broader geographical category for G1 tags eg\. Arabic
__Cuisine \(3\): Main value prop tag: __Must be from the corresponding Food tags or General tags list of the selected G1/G2 tags or the non\-geographical cuisine tag list\.

1. __Cuisine Tag 1 \(G1\): __Represents country\-specific cuisine and must be sourced from the MIF\. If multiple tags are provided from the same tree \(e\.g\., Emirati, Saudi, Egyptian\), the Catalog team will select a G2 tag\. If the tags come from different trees, the Catalog team will choose the G1 tag based on the partner’s menu and outlet name\. 2. __Cuisine Tag 2 \(G2\)__: Represents the broader geographical category for G1 tags eg\. Arabic
__Cuisine \(3\): Main value prop tag: __Must be from the corresponding food tags or general tags list of the selected G1/G2 tags or the non\-geographical cuisine tag list\.

title: SOP_ Menu Tags Guidelines (1).docx — 4\.2\.2 UAE tags policies (part 1)
text:
Tags policies are shared below:
__Cuisine Tags:__
1. Ensure that 50% of the menu reflects the primary value proposition, focusing on key categories or menu items
2. Use the outlet name as a key indicator of the value proposition\. For instance, if the restaurant is named "Pasta Italy," categorize pasta as the main cuisine based on the restaurant's name
3. Up to 3 cuisine tags can be selected
4. Cuisine tag 3 can be either 0 or 1
5. Cuisine tag 3 must be selected from the food or general tags list associated with the chosen G1/G2 tags or from the non\-geographical cuisine tag list
6. If the partner provides 2 G1 tags from the same tree in the MIF, apply both G1s provided by them along with G2\. For example, if the MIF lists Emirati and Kuwaiti, add Emirati, Kuwaiti, add Arabic to the profile
7. Both G1 tags should be from the same tree\. If they are from different trees, the Catalog team will select the G1 tag based on the partner’s menu and the outlet name Incorrect Example: Emirati, Saudi, Japanese

text:
Cuisine tags are divided into G1 and G2 types\. The repository linked below guides mapping G1 tags, and G2 tags against the Cuisine tags\. 1. __Cuisine Tag 1 \(G1\): __Represents country\-specific cuisine and must be sourced from the MIF\. If multiple tags are provided, and they come from the same tree \(e\.g\., Emirati, Saudi, Egyptian\), then G2 needs to be picked by the Catalog team\. If the tags come from different trees, the Catalog team will select the G1 tag based on the partner’s menu and the outlet name\. 2. __Cuisine Tag 2 \(G2\)__: Represents the broader geographical category for G1 tags eg\. Arabic
